"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 13–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-13-14.py

Historical/cultural/geographical context focus only.
NOT Greek lexical analysis (mkt-original) and NOT typology/Christology (mkt-christ).

Key context decisions for this range:
- Ch13 parable discourse: Jewish mashal tradition, Isaiah 6 hardening, seven parables
- Sower: Palestinian broadcast-sowing (sow first, plow after); four soil types mapped to Galilee terrain
- Darnel (zizanion): Lolium temulentum, looks identical to wheat until grain appears
- Mustard seed: Sinapis alba, grows to 8-10 ft shrub in Palestinian climate; birds = Gentile nations
- Leaven: normally negative image in Jewish law (purity), here as positive transformative agent
- Hidden treasure: ancient near-eastern practice of burying valuables in clay jars in fields
- Pearl: Persian Gulf and Red Sea pearl trade; merchants who specialized in precious pearls
- Dragnet (sagene): commercial seine net used on Sea of Galilee; clean/unclean fish from Lev 11
- Nazareth rejection: 14:13 following immediately, village social memory of Jesus' family
- Ch14: Herod's birthday banquet, Josephus account (Ant. 18.116-119) parallel
- Five thousand: crowd as an impromptu assembly in the wilderness with Passover approach
- v13:1 and v14:6 already present; merge_comm will skip them
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: Historical/cultural/geographical context for Matthew 13-14; covers the
#   Parable Discourse and the transition to the Galilean lake miracles.
# CHANGE? If verse keys change in data/interlinear/matthew.json, update dict keys here.
# VERIFY: Run script; confirm ch13 = 58 verses, ch14 = 36 verses in output.

MATTHEW = {
  "13": {
    "2": '<p>The crowd gathered by the sea (<em>para tēn thalassan</em>) was so large that Jesus boarded a boat and sat in it while teaching from the water — the boat\xe2\x80\x99s deck serving as an elevated platform visible to the crowd on the shore. The natural amphitheater formed by the curved shoreline at Capernaum/Gennesaret would have provided excellent acoustics for a teacher speaking from a boat a short distance offshore. This was an outdoor teaching occasion of unusual scale, distinct from synagogue teaching.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Parables (<em>meshalim</em>) were a standard Jewish teaching form: a short narrative or comparison that made an abstract truth accessible through concrete imagery. Ezekiel, Nathan, and Amos all used mashal-forms; rabbinic literature preserved hundreds of meshalim. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 parables share the form but introduce distinctive elements — particularly the reversal-of-expectations structure and the consistent focus on the kingdom of heaven as the reality being described. The parable of the sower opens the discourse with an agricultural scene familiar to every peasant farmer in Galilee.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Palestinian agricultural practice typically involved broadcast sowing (scattering seed widely) before plowing it under, rather than the reverse. This means the sower deliberately sowed on paths, rocky ground, and among thorns before the field was prepared — the seed would land on all types of ground before any selective plowing. The path (<em>hē hodos</em>) alongside or through a field was hard-packed by foot traffic; seed falling there would lie on the surface and be immediately available to birds.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Rocky ground (<em>ta petrōdē</em>) is a characteristic feature of Galilean terrain: a thin layer of soil over bedrock limestone. Such soil warms quickly in spring (enabling fast germination) but has no depth for the root system to develop, and dries out rapidly in summer heat. The visual reality of green shoots springing up quickly in such soil, then withering as the ground dried, was an annually observable agricultural event for Galilean farmers.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The scorching sun (<em>hēliou anateilantos ekaumatisthē</em>) in the Palestinian summer (June-August) could reach temperatures over 40\xe2\x80\xb0C (104\xe2\x80\xb0F). Shallow-rooted plants growing in thin soil over limestone had no water reserve to draw on during the hot season. The agricultural reality was stark: without adequate root depth, the same rapid growth that characterized shallow-soil plants became a death sentence once the summer heat arrived.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Thorns and thorn-bushes (<em>akanthai</em>) were ubiquitous in Palestinian fields. The most common thorny weed was the Syrian thistle (<em>Notobasis syriaca</em>) or the bramble (<em>Rubus ulmifolius</em>). These grew vigorously and could overtop and choke grain crops within the same season. Fallowed ground that had not been thoroughly plowed might contain dormant thorn seeds or roots that would compete with deliberately sown grain.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Good soil producing hundredfold, sixtyfold, and thirtyfold reflects realistic but high-yield Palestinian grain harvests. Normal wheat yields in first-century Palestine ranged from 5:1 to 10:1 (five to ten grains harvested for each sown); yields of 30:1 to 100:1 represent extraordinarily good harvests that would be recognized as exceptional. The descending order (hundred, sixty, thirty) rather than ascending is not a hierarchy of merit but an acknowledgment of variable yield within a category of genuine fruitfulness.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Let the one who has ears hear" — the formula marks teaching that requires interpretive engagement beyond surface hearing. It is used in the Synoptics (9:9, 43; Mark 4:9) and Revelation to signal teaching with multiple layers of meaning. In the context of the parable discourse, it signals that the agricultural narrative contains kingdom-meaning that requires active discernment — not everyone who hears the parable will understand what it describes.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question — "Why do you speak to them in parables?" — reflects a genuine question about pedagogical strategy. The shift from direct teaching (Sermon on the Mount) to parabolic teaching occurs at the narrative turning point where official opposition (Beelzebul controversy, demand for a sign) has crystallized. Parables functioned in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching both as vehicles of revelation for receptive hearers and as forms of concealment for those whose spiritual perception had hardened.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"To you it has been given to know the mysteries of the kingdom of heaven" — the "mysteries" (<em>mystēria</em>) language derives from Jewish apocalyptic literature (Dan 2:18-19, 27-30; 1 En. 41, 46; 1QpHab 7:5), where God\xe2\x80\x99s hidden purposes, concealed from the wise of this age, are revealed to the elect. The Dead Sea Scrolls speak extensively of divine <em>razim</em> (mysteries) disclosed to the community through inspired interpretation. Jesus places himself in the role of the apocalyptic revealer who discloses what was hidden.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"For to the one who has, more will be given, and he will have an abundance, but from the one who has not, even what he has will be taken away" — the principle of accumulative reception reflects the dynamics of knowledge and spiritual perception in any discipline. In Jewish wisdom tradition, wisdom multiplied for those who pursued it and diminished for those who neglected it (cf. Prov 1:5; Sir 18:28). Applied to the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s mysteries, the principle describes the self-reinforcing nature of receptive hearing: each insight creates capacity for more.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"This is why I speak to them in parables, because seeing they do not see, and hearing they do not hear, nor do they understand" — the parable\xe2\x80\x99s simultaneous revelation/concealment function is grounded in the empirical fact of divided response. The same teaching produces understanding in some and incomprehension in others, not because the teaching is deliberately obscure but because the capacity for reception differs. The following citation of Isaiah 6 provides the prophetic framework for this divided response.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The citation of Isa 6:9-10 — "You will indeed hear but never understand, and you will indeed see but never perceive" — is among the most frequently cited OT passages in the NT (Mark 4:12; Luke 8:10; John 12:40; Acts 28:26-27; Rom 11:8). Isaiah 6 is the prophet\xe2\x80\x99s commission: he is sent to a people whose hearts have been made fat, ears heavy, and eyes shut. The NT uses this passage to explain why Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 proclamation met with widespread rejection rather than the universal response one might have expected from the Messiah\xe2\x80\x99s arrival.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Isaiah 6\xe2\x80\x99s language of the fat heart (<em>pachyntē hē kardia tou laou toutou</em>), heavy ears, and shut eyes describes a condition of voluntary and judicial hardening: the people have closed their own perception, and God has confirmed that closure as judgment. The sequence — "lest they perceive... and turn, and I would heal them" — frames the hardening as mercy\xe2\x80\x99s opposite: those who would not return receive the confirmation of their refusal. Matthew applies this to the generation that witnessed Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 signs and rejected them.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"But blessed are your eyes, for they see, and your ears, for they hear" — the Beatitude is addressed to disciples who are presented as experiencing what the prophets longed for but did not receive. The contrast with the hardened crowd is not about the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 inherent superiority but about the gift of receptive perception that they have received: they are in the position of those to whom the mysteries are given (v. 11).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, many prophets and righteous people longed to see what you see, and did not see it, and to hear what you hear, and did not hear it" — the prophets\xe2\x80\x99 longing for the eschatological fulfillment they announced was a recognized theme in Jewish thought. The Qumran community explicitly stated that the prophets did not know the full meaning of what they prophesied, which was being revealed to the community in their time (1QpHab 7:1-5). The disciples are presented as living in the age the prophets could only anticipate.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The transition "hear then the parable of the sower" moves from the metadiscourse about parables to the explanation of the specific parable. The explanation was addressed to the disciples privately (v. 36: "he left the crowds and went into the house"), distinguishing between the public parable (heard by all) and the private explanation (given to the receptive inner circle). This pattern of public proclamation and private instruction is characteristic of the Markan/Matthean Jesus.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"The evil one comes and snatches away what has been sown in his heart" — the path-seed represents those who hear the word but have no internal reception space; it remains on the surface where the adversary removes it. In Jewish demonology, the "evil one" (<em>ho ponēros</em>) was the personal opponent of God\xe2\x80\x99s purposes; the Qumran texts described the "spirit of darkness" actively opposing the truth. The immediate passive removal of the word describes a hearing without any inner engagement.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The rocky ground represents those who receive the word with immediate enthusiasm (<em>meta charas</em> = with joy) but have no root. In first-century terms, this describes the typical response to charismatic popular movements: initial enthusiastic crowds who follow on the basis of excitement but lack the depth of commitment to survive opposition. The crowds who acclaimed Jesus on Palm Sunday and abandoned him before the Passion may illustrate exactly this pattern.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Tribulation or persecution arises on account of the word" — the social cost of discipleship in the first-century context was real and varied: synagogue exclusion, family division (cf. 10:35-36), loss of economic relationships, and in some cases legal jeopardy. The shallow-rooted hearer "immediately falls away" (<em>euthys skandalizetai</em>) — the Passion narrative\xe2\x80\x99s scattering of the disciples is itself an illustration of this pattern at the level of the Twelve.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The thorny ground represents those whose word-reception is choked by "the cares of the age and the deceitfulness of riches" (<em>hē merimna tou aiōnos kai hē apatē tou ploutou</em>). "Cares of the age" points to the economic anxieties of subsistence-level peasant life: concern about food, clothing, shelter — the survival concerns Jesus addressed in the Sermon (6:25-34). "Deceitfulness of riches" points to the other end: wealth that promises security but substitutes mammon-anxiety for kingdom-trust. Both are described as thorns that choke without appearing to — the grain looks normal until it never produces.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The good soil that bears fruit in varying amounts (hundredfold, sixty, thirty) represents the range of productive reception, not a hierarchy of merit. Jewish Wisdom literature described fruitful reception of instruction as the goal of formation: "plant wisdom in yourself and you will reap it in abundance" (Sir 6:19-20 LXX). The variable yields (100, 60, 30) acknowledge that genuine fruitfulness takes many forms and magnitudes — the criterion is production, not uniformity.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The parable of the weeds (<em>zizania</em>) is unique to Matthew and addressed to the crowds, followed by private explanation for the disciples (vv. 36-43). The sowing of weeds in an enemy\xe2\x80\x99s field was a recognized act of agricultural sabotage in antiquity: Digest 9.2.27.14 (Roman law) mentions sowing weeds in another\xe2\x80\x99s crop as a specific legal offense. The enemy who "came and sowed weeds among the wheat and went away" describes a nocturnal sabotage act — real enough to be legally categorized in Roman law.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The specific weed described is <em>zizanion</em> — identified with <em>Lolium temulentum</em> (darnel), a grass indistinguishable from wheat in its early growth stages. Its roots intertwine with wheat roots at the seedling stage; early removal would uproot both. The grain of darnel is a small dark seed that is mildly toxic (containing the fungal alkaloid temuline) and was a genuine agricultural problem in ancient Palestinian grain fields. Only at harvest, when the full heads of grain vs. the narrow darnel seed appear, can they be reliably distinguished and separated.</p>',
    "26": '<p>When the grain appeared (<em>blastan</em> = sprouted), the darnel (<em>zizania</em>) also appeared — visually distinct for the first time by the character of their grain. The servants\xe2\x80\x99 discovery of the mixed field at this point reflects the agricultural reality: early in the season, you could not know; at grain-head stage, the contamination becomes visible. The parable exploits this agricultural fact to describe the mixed nature of the present kingdom community.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The servants\xe2\x80\x99 question — "Master, did you not sow good seed in your field? Where then did the weeds come from?" — reflects the natural management question for a Palestinian farmer: is this natural contamination (cross-pollination, wind-blown seeds) or deliberate sabotage? The master\xe2\x80\x99s answer ("an enemy has done this") identifies the source as intentional hostility rather than accident, activating the legal framework of agricultural sabotage.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The servants\xe2\x80\x99 proposed solution — "Do you want us to go and gather them?" — reflects the natural response: immediate removal. The master\xe2\x80\x99s refusal is counter-intuitive from a farming perspective (darnel infestation worsens each year) but is grounded in the practical reality of root entanglement and the parable\xe2\x80\x99s theological purpose: premature judgment would destroy the wheat along with the weeds.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"No, lest in gathering the weeds you root up the wheat along with them" — the agricultural logic is sound for the seedling stage where root systems are intertwined, but at harvest the plants are mature and can be individually cut. The delayed separation until harvest maps the eschatological judgment: the present age is not the time for definitive separation of the righteous and the wicked; that is the prerogative of the harvesters (angels) at the end of the age.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The harvest command — "gather the weeds first and bind them in bundles to be burned, but gather the wheat into my barn" — reverses the order from agricultural practice (normally good grain gathered first) to emphasize the priority of removing the weeds. Darnel straw was usable as fuel; it was typically bundled separately from wheat for burning in bread ovens or lime kilns. The agricultural detail supports the theological point: what was mixed and indistinguishable during growth is definitively separated and differently disposed of at harvest.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The mustard seed (<em>kokkō sinapeos</em>) was proverbially the smallest seed in Jewish tradition (m. Niddah 5:2: "the smallest of all seeds"). The specific species is likely <em>Sinapis alba</em> (white mustard) or <em>Sinapis nigra</em> (black mustard), both common in Palestinian fields and gardens. While the seed is small, the plant grows to 8-10 feet (2.5-3 meters) in Palestinian climate — unusually large for what is technically an annual herb rather than a tree.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"The birds of the air come and make nests in its branches" — in the OT, birds nesting in a large tree is a standard image for the nations finding shelter under the protection of a great empire (Dan 4:12, 21 uses it for Nebuchadnezzar\xe2\x80\x99s Babylon; Ezek 17:23 for Israel\xe2\x80\x99s restoration; 31:6 for Egypt). The Gentile nations finding shelter in the mustard-tree kingdom was an image the Jewish audience would have recognized as pointing beyond Israel to an inclusive scope. The kingdom starts invisibly small (one itinerant teacher) and grows to encompass the nations.</p>',
    "33": '<p>Leaven (<em>zymē</em>) in Jewish culture was predominantly a negative symbol: leavened bread was forbidden during Passover (Exod 12:15-20; 13:7); leaven was a metaphor for sin and corruption in Pauline usage (1 Cor 5:6-8; Gal 5:9). The parable\xe2\x80\x99s use of leaven as a positive image for the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s transformation is therefore surprising and possibly deliberately subversive of conventional associations. Three measures (<em>sata tria</em>) of meal equaled approximately 40 liters — enough for a large communal baking (Abraham\xe2\x80\x99s hospitality in Gen 18:6 also uses three measures, a possible allusion).</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Jesus said all these things to the crowds in parables; indeed, he said nothing to them without a parable" — Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s summary statement generalizes the parabolic teaching method as characteristic of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 public discourse at this point in his ministry. This functions as a narrative note explaining the discourse structure: the crowds receive parables, the disciples receive explanations. The statement sets up the following citation of Psalm 78:2.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The citation of Ps 78:2 — "I will open my mouth in parables; I will utter what has been hidden since the foundation of the world" — identifies Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 parabolic teaching as the fulfillment of Asaph\xe2\x80\x99s promise. Psalm 78 is a historical psalm (<em>maskil</em> of Asaph) retelling Israel\xe2\x80\x99s covenant history from the Exodus through David; the promise to "speak in parables" refers to making hidden wisdom accessible through narrative form. Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s "hidden since the foundation of the world" expands the psalm\xe2\x80\x99s scope to the primordial — what Jesus reveals in parables is not merely Israel\xe2\x80\x99s history but the cosmos\xe2\x80\x99 foundational purposes.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 return to the house (<em>apheis tous ochlous elthen eis tēn oikian</em>) creates the private instruction setting for the disciples. The house was the standard Jewish teaching venue for intimate instruction; rabbinic schools met in the teacher\xe2\x80\x99s house. The distinction between public teaching (parables to crowds) and private explanation (house for disciples) structured Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 pedagogical practice — the disciples were being formed as the community that would transmit the explanations.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"The one who sows the good seed is the Son of Man" — the allegorical explanation identifies each element of the parable precisely. The Son of Man as sower positions Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry as the act that introduces the kingdom mixture into the world. The allegorical method here is closer to the pesher interpretation of the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QpHab) than to typical rabbinic parable: each element has a one-to-one correspondence with a reality in the eschatological drama.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"The field is the world" — notably not "the field is Israel" or "the field is the church." The parable operates on the cosmic scale: the mixed community of righteous and wicked exists throughout the <em>kosmos</em>, not just within one nation or community. "The sons of the kingdom" and "the sons of the evil one" are technical designations from apocalyptic dualism (similar to Qumran\xe2\x80\x99s "sons of light" and "sons of darkness," 1QS 3:13-4:26) — they describe fundamental orientation rather than moral perfection.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"The harvest is the end of the age, and the reapers are angels" — the harvest as a metaphor for eschatological judgment has deep OT roots (Joel 3:13; Isa 27:12; Jer 51:33). The angels as eschatological agents of judgment appears in Jewish apocalyptic literature (1 En. 56:1-4; 63:1) and throughout Revelation. The end of the age (<em>synteleia tou aiōnos</em>) is the technical term for the eschatological transition from the present age to the coming age — a concept central to Second Temple Jewish eschatology.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The burning of the darnel at the end of the age activates the standard apocalyptic fire-of-judgment imagery. Fire as the agent of eschatological purification/destruction appears throughout the prophets (Isa 66:15-16; Mal 4:1; Zeph 1:18) and Jewish apocalyptic texts. The "furnace of fire" (<em>kaminos tou pyros</em>) is a specific image that recalls Dan 3\xe2\x80\x99s furnace — though there the righteous were preserved in the fire rather than the wicked burned by it.</p>',
    "41": '<p>"The Son of Man will send his angels, and they will gather out of his kingdom all causes of sin and all law-breakers" — the eschatological kingdom gathering in reverse: rather than gathering the righteous in, the angels gather out the causes of stumbling (<em>skandala</em>) and those who practice lawlessness (<em>anomia</em>). The phrase "causes of sin" (<em>panta ta skandala</em>) refers to the things and people that cause others to fall — a category that includes both deceiving teachers and systemic corruptions of the community.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"The furnace of fire" with "weeping and gnashing of teeth" (<em>klauthnos kai brygmos tōn odontōn</em>) — the weeping/gnashing formula appears six times in Matthew (8:12; 13:42, 50; 22:13; 24:51; 25:30) and once in Luke (13:28), functioning as Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s standard description of eschatological suffering. "Gnashing of teeth" in Jewish texts (Ps 112:10; Lam 2:16) expresses rage, anguish, or despair. The combination describes the intense emotional state of those experiencing the consequences of their choices.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"Then the righteous will shine like the sun in the kingdom of their Father" echoes Dan 12:3 ("those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above, and those who turn many to righteousness, like the stars forever and ever"). The Daniel reference locates the promise within the resurrection and vindication tradition of Jewish apocalyptic: those who endured faithfully through persecution and hardening will be publicly vindicated and transformed in eschatological glory.</p>',
    "44": '<p>The hidden treasure parable draws on the common ancient near-eastern practice of burying valuables — coins, jewelry, family wealth — in clay jars in one\xe2\x80\x99s field as protection against theft, raiding, or political upheaval. Palestine\xe2\x80\x99s turbulent history (Babylonian conquest, Ptolemaic-Seleucid conflicts, Roman occupation) meant that the sudden death of a property-owner could leave buried valuables undiscovered for generations. Archaeological excavations in Israel regularly uncover coin hoards from precisely this kind of emergency burial. The finder of such a hoard had a windfall claim if he acted quickly and legally.</p>',
    "45": '<p>The pearl merchant (<em>emporos</em> = traveling merchant, wholesale dealer) who seeks fine pearls represents a different social type from the field-discoverer: a professional whose entire economic life is organized around acquiring and trading pearls. Pearls in the ancient world came primarily from the Persian Gulf (Bahrain), the Red Sea, and the Indian Ocean; they were among the most valued luxury commodities of the Roman world, fetching extraordinary prices. First-century Rome had a pearl craze: Pliny (Natural History 9.54-58) records individual pearls worth millions of sesterces.</p>',
    "46": '<p>"On finding one pearl of great value, he went and sold all that he had and bought it" — the merchant\xe2\x80\x99s action of liquidating his entire inventory to acquire one supreme pearl was a recognizable business logic: if you find something worth more than everything else you possess, rational self-interest demands conversion. The parable does not romanticize the merchant\xe2\x80\x99s decision as sacrifice; it presents it as the obvious rational response to the discovery of supreme value. The kingdom similarly demands total reorientation because it is genuinely worth more than any alternative.</p>',
    "47": '<p>The dragnet (<em>sagēnē</em>) was a large seine or drag net used for commercial fishing — different from the smaller cast-net (<em>amphiblestron</em>) used by Peter and Andrew. A drag net was a large mesh bag weighted at the bottom and floated at the top that was drawn through the water (sometimes by two boats) to capture everything in its path. The Sea of Galilee supported a significant commercial fishing industry; first-century excavations at Magdala (Tarichaeae) have found evidence of large fish-processing operations. The dragnet\xe2\x80\x99s indiscriminate capture ("of every kind") is the parable\xe2\x80\x99s key agricultural-economic fact.</p>',
    "48": '<p>Sorting the catch on the shore (<em>kathisantes syneléxan ta kala eis aggeē ta de sapra exō ebalon</em>) reflected both economic necessity and Jewish purity law. Commercially, different species had different market values; inedible or damaged fish were culled. Religiously, Lev 11:9-12 and Deut 14:9-10 defined clean fish (having fins and scales) and unclean fish (those lacking them) — catfish, eels, and other scaleless species were ritually impure and could not be sold to observant Jews. The sorting was both commercial grading and ritual classification.</p>',
    "49": '<p>"So it will be at the end of the age" — the parable explicitly claims eschatological significance: the present mixed community (like the dragnet\xe2\x80\x99s catch) will be definitively sorted at the end of the age by angels. The parable\xe2\x80\x99s context (after the weeds parable and its explanation) underlines the consistency of the theme: the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s present reality is mixed and incomplete; its eschatological reality will be purified and definitive.</p>',
    "50": '<p>The "furnace of fire" and "weeping and gnashing of teeth" repeat the weeds parable\xe2\x80\x99s eschatological closing (v. 42) — a rhetorical anaphora that reinforces the twin parables\xe2\x80\x99 shared conclusion. The repetition signals that this is not incidental imagery but the core claim: the same world that appears mixed and undifferentiated now will be precisely and definitively sorted then. The emotional description of the wicked\xe2\x80\x99s final state functions as a warning rather than as theological precision about the nature of eschatological punishment.</p>',
    "51": '<p>"Have you understood all these things?" — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 direct question to the disciples after the private explanations tests their comprehension and completion of the parabolic instruction. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 "yes" is a narrative statement of their having received the inside knowledge — in contrast to the crowds who heard but did not understand. The question also introduces the final parable of the scribe trained for the kingdom.</p>',
    "52": '<p>The scribe trained for the kingdom of heaven (<em>grammateus mathēteutheis tē̄ basileia̧ tōn ouranōn</em>) who brings out from his storehouse (<em>thēsaurou</em>) both new and old describes the ideal disciple-transmitter. The scribe was the professional custodian and interpreter of written texts in ancient Jewish life — the one who read, copied, and explained Torah and the prophetic scrolls. A scribe "discipled for the kingdom" combines the traditioned learning of Jewish scribal culture with the new kingdom-perspective Jesus has been teaching. Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s community, which carefully preserved Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching in writing, is implicitly this kind of scribe.</p>',
    "53": '<p>The closing formula "when Jesus had finished these parables" (<em>hote etelesen ho Iēsous tas parabolois tautas</em>) is the third of the five discourse-closing formulas in Matthew (7:28; 11:1; 13:53; 19:1; 26:1). The five-discourse structure mirrors the Pentateuch\xe2\x80\x99s five books — a deliberate structural choice that presents Jesus as the new Moses delivering the new Torah. The departure to "his own country" (<em>tēn patrida autou</em>) sets up the Nazareth rejection.</p>',
    "54": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 return to his hometown (<em>patrida autou</em> = Nazareth) and teaching in their synagogue produced astonishment (<em>exeplēssonto</em>) and offense (<em>eskandalizonto</em>). The astonishment was at the content — "where did this man get this wisdom and these mighty works?" — while the offense was rooted in social memory: they knew his family, his trade, and his ordinary origins. In a village social system where one\xe2\x80\x99s identity was entirely determined by family lineage and local reputation, claims to extraordinary authority from a known local were socially intolerable.</p>',
    "55": '<p>"Is not this the carpenter\xe2\x80\x99s son?" — the identification of Jesus as a craftsman\xe2\x80\x99s son (<em>tou tektonos huios</em>) is socially precise. The <em>tektōn</em> (craftsman/carpenter/builder) was a skilled artisan of modest social status — above landless day-laborers but below landowners and merchants. His mother and brothers (James, Joseph, Simon, Judas) were all known members of the Nazareth community. The naming of Mary and the brothers is not merely genealogical detail but social identification: "We know these people — how can he be more than he appears to be?"</p>',
    "56": '<p>The sisters (<em>hai adelphai autou</em>) are mentioned without being named, consistent with the lower social visibility of women in public discourse. Their presence in Nazareth suggests that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 family\xe2\x80\x99s base remained in Nazareth while Jesus operated from Capernaum. The comprehensive identification of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 family network in vv. 55-56 underscores the social impossibility (in their framework) of attributing extraordinary authority to someone so thoroughly known and ordinary.</p>',
    "57": '<p>"A prophet is not without honor except in his hometown and in his own household" — the proverb was recognized in the ancient world as a general social observation: familiarity breeds contempt for extraordinary gifts. Epictetus (Discourses 3.16.11) and other Hellenistic writers use similar observations. In the Jewish context, the prophets consistently faced rejection from their own communities (Jer 11:21; 12:6; Amos 7:10-13). The proverb frames the Nazareth rejection within a recognized pattern of prophetic experience.</p>',
    "58": '<p>"He did not do many mighty works there, because of their unbelief" — the connection between unbelief and limited healings is not presented as a mechanical limitation on divine power but as a covenantal dynamic: the healing miracles functioned within a relationship of faith-response; their absence when that relationship was absent reflected the nature of the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s operation. The healings in Matthew consistently involve faith (9:22, 29; 15:28); their absence in Nazareth reflects the absence of the trust that constituted receptive participation in kingdom restoration.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>Herod the tetrarch (<em>ho tetrarchēs</em>) is Herod Antipas, son of Herod the Great, who ruled Galilee and Peraea (4 BCE-39 CE) as a Roman client tetrarch. A tetrarchy was a quarter-kingdom — Antipas ruled one of four divisions created when Herod the Great\xe2\x80\x99s kingdom was divided among his sons. He was not a king but a tetrarch, though Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative will call him "king" (v. 9) — the popular courtesy title for a ruler who aspired to royal status. Antipas maintained a dual court at Tiberias (on the Sea of Galilee, built ca. 20 CE) and at Machaerus (east of the Dead Sea).</p>',
    "2": '<p>"This is John the Baptist. He has been raised from the dead; that is why these miraculous powers are at work in him" — Herod\xe2\x80\x99s superstitious fear reflects the popular Jewish belief in miraculous powers associated with resurrection. The connection between resurrection and supernatural power was grounded in the prophetic tradition: Elijah\xe2\x80\x99s miracles continued to have power even after his translation (2 Kgs 13:21 describes a dead man revived by contact with Elisha\xe2\x80\x99s bones). Herod\xe2\x80\x99s confession is a recognition of John\xe2\x80\x99s holiness and his own guilt, not a theological statement about resurrection.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Herod had imprisoned John at Machaerus (Josephus, <em>Ant.</em> 18.116-119) after John publicly condemned his marriage to Herodias, his brother Philip\xe2\x80\x99s wife. The Josephus account gives a different primary motivation for the imprisonment (fear of John\xe2\x80\x99s political influence) while Matthew focuses on the personal vendetta. The two accounts are complementary: Herod\xe2\x80\x99s personal embarrassment at John\xe2\x80\x99s public rebuke and political fear of a popular prophetic figure both motivated the arrest.</p>',
    "4": '<p>John\xe2\x80\x99s rebuke — "It is not lawful for you to have her" (<em>ouk exestin soi echein autēn</em>) — refers to Lev 18:16 and 20:21, which prohibited marriage to a brother\xe2\x80\x99s wife while the brother was living. Philip\xe2\x80\x99s marriage to Herodias produced a daughter (Salome); when Antipas persuaded Herodias to leave Philip and marry him, he violated the Levitical prohibition. This was not merely a private moral failing but a public violation of covenant law by a ruler over Israel — precisely the kind of prophetic confrontation of royal sin that characterized Elijah\xe2\x80\x99s confrontation with Ahab and Jezebel (1 Kgs 21).</p>',
    "5": '<p>"He wanted to put him to death, but he feared the people, because they held him to be a prophet" — the political calculus is precise: killing John would provoke popular backlash from the masses who revered him. Josephus confirms this: "Herod feared that John\xe2\x80\x99s great influence over people might lead to some form of revolt, for they seemed ready to do anything he might advise" (<em>Ant.</em> 18.118). The tension between Herod\xe2\x80\x99s desire to eliminate John and his fear of popular reaction was exactly resolved by the birthday banquet opportunity.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Herod\xe2\x80\x99s oath "to give her whatever she might ask" with an audience of guests present invoked the honor-obligation mechanism of the patron-client system. A public oath before one\xe2\x80\x99s guests created an irrevocable social obligation: to refuse would be to lose face before the court. The rash oath formula "whatever she might ask, up to half my kingdom" (Mark 6:23) deliberately echoes Esth 5:3 and 7:2 (Ahasuerus\xe2\x80\x99 offer to Esther) — a literary allusion that frames the scene as a dark inversion of Esther\xe2\x80\x99s righteous petition.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Prompted by her mother, she said, \'Give me the head of John the Baptist here on a platter\'" — the request represents the transformation of a birthday gift into a public execution. "Here" (<em>hōde</em>) and "on a platter" (<em>epi pinaki</em>) indicate that Herodias wanted the deed done immediately and the proof brought into the banquet room — ensuring no diplomatic retreat for Antipas. The platter detail emphasizes the grotesquerie: a banquet vessel for a victim\xe2\x80\x99s head. Josephus identifies the dancing girl as Salome, daughter of Herodias by Philip.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"The king was sorry, but because of his oaths and his guests he commanded it to be given" — the honorific "king" (<em>ho basileus</em>) in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative is ironic: it is precisely his royal pretension that traps him. Having publicly sworn before his court and guests (<em>tous synanakeimenous</em>), he had no face-saving option other than compliance. The social machinery of honor-shame culture and patron-client oath-obligation overrode his personal reluctance — a narrative that indicts not only Herod\xe2\x80\x99s weakness but the court culture that made this inevitable.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The execution at Machaerus fortress — "he sent and had John beheaded in the prison" (<em>apekefalisen Iōannēn en tē̄ phylakē̄</em>) — was a private, summary execution without trial. Antipas had no legal authority to execute a subject for criticizing his marriage under Jewish or Roman law; this was an extrajudicial murder motivated by personal and political calculation. The action would later be cited in Josephus as a cause of the military defeat Antipas suffered at the hands of Aretas IV of Nabataea, whose daughter Antipas had divorced to marry Herodias (<em>Ant.</em> 18.114-115).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The head brought on a platter to the girl and then to her mother completes the dark transaction initiated by the oath. The public setting of the banquet meant that the execution\xe2\x80\x99s completion would have been witnessed by the assembled court — the social function of honor-restoration was accomplished publicly. John\xe2\x80\x99s disciples coming to take his body and bury it reflects the Jewish obligation of proper burial as an act of piety; the Essenes and other Jewish groups considered burying the dead — especially the executed — a critical duty.</p>',
    "12": '<p>John\xe2\x80\x99s disciples coming to bury him and then reporting to Jesus creates the narrative connection between John\xe2\x80\x99s execution and Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal. Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s arrangement — the execution narrative interrupting the mission of the Twelve (between their sending in 10:1-42 and their return) — frames John\xe2\x80\x99s death as a prophetic anticipation of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own passion. The report to Jesus triggers his withdrawal, signaling the danger his own ministry faced from the Herodian power structure.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal by boat to "a desolate place apart" (<em>erēmon topon kat\xe2\x80\x99 idian</em>) upon hearing of John\xe2\x80\x99s death was both a practical security measure and a deliberate retreat for mourning. The Sea of Galilee\xe2\x80\x99s northeastern shore, near Bethsaida (Luke 9:10), was sparsely populated territory partially outside Herod Antipas\xe2\x80\x99s jurisdiction (in Philip\xe2\x80\x99s territory). The crowds who followed on foot from the surrounding towns represented the persistent population that would not be managed by Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal — their following was itself a demonstration of the popular pressure that made Herod fear a revolt.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Seeing the crowd, Jesus had compassion (<em>esplagchnisthē</em>) and healed the sick. The verb <em>splagchnizomai</em> (to feel deep compassion, from <em>splagchna</em> = entrails, the seat of deep emotion in Greek) describes the most visceral form of compassionate response. The healing in the context of his own grief and political danger presents Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry as constitutively compassionate — he cannot encounter suffering without responding to it, even in his own moment of loss.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 request to dismiss the crowd "to go into the villages and buy food for themselves" reflects the practical geography: the northeastern lakeshore near Bethsaida was not a village but a desolate (wilderness) area. Surrounding villages would have had food available for purchase; the crowd of several thousand had apparently followed Jesus without provision for an extended stay. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 concern is organizational-practical, not hard-hearted: with no food infrastructure in the desolate location and evening approaching, feeding the crowd was genuinely impossible through normal means.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"They need not go away; you give them something to eat" — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 counter-instruction places the responsibility with the disciples rather than the crowd. This is both a test of the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 understanding of his identity and a preparation for the miracle\xe2\x80\x99s significance. The Passover proximity (John 6:4 specifies that the Passover was near) means the crowd in the wilderness with their leader distributing bread had strong Exodus resonances: Moses distributing manna in the wilderness, the eschatological banquet of the messianic age.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"We have only five loaves here and two fish" — the inventory of the available food is deliberately minimal: five barley loaves (the bread of the poor; John 6:9 specifies barley) and two fish (<em>ichthyas duo</em> = dried or salted fish, the standard protein supplement to bread in Galilean peasant diet). The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 response implicitly acknowledges the inadequacy of their resources for a crowd of five thousand men (plus women and children, v. 21) — making the miracle\xe2\x80\x99s scale visible.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The instruction "bring them here to me" — the five loaves and two fish brought to Jesus — is the pivot between the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 inadequate resources and Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 action. The pattern (take, give thanks, break, distribute) will be replicated at the Last Supper (26:26-27), creating a deliberate intertextual connection between this feeding and the Eucharistic institution. Early Christian communities reading this narrative would have recognized the eucharistic form immediately.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 command to recline (<em>anaklinai</em>) on the grass before distributing food organizes the crowd into manageable groups for distribution (Mark 6:39-40 specifies groups of hundreds and fifties). The blessing and breaking of bread followed the standard Jewish meal-blessing (<em>birkat hamazon</em>): the householder blessed God for the bread, broke it, and distributed it. The structure was immediately recognizable as a meal-opening ritual. The disciples distributing to the crowds enacts the mission they had just returned from: serving as extension of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The twelve baskets of fragments gathered (<em>dōdeka kophinous plēreis klasmatōn</em>) are twelve, not incidentally. The <em>kophinos</em> was a distinctively Jewish wicker basket used by Jewish travelers (Juvenal, Satire 3.14, mocks Jews carrying kophinos baskets); twelve baskets gathered by twelve disciples after feeding the crowds provides an image of eschatological abundance — more remains after the miracle than existed before. The twelve baskets may also gesture toward the twelve tribes: the new Israel is fully provided for.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"And those who ate were about five thousand men, besides women and children" — the count of men only (<em>hoi esthiontes... chōris gynaikōn kai paidiōn</em>) follows the standard ancient census convention (counting adult males as the representative unit of a household). The actual total, including women and children, may have been 15,000-20,000. A crowd of this size in a wilderness location with a single leader who has just fed them would have created exactly the kind of political situation that Roman client-kings feared: a potential popular movement prepared to make him king (John 6:15 explicitly states this intention).</p>',
    "22": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 immediate compulsion of the disciples to leave by boat ("immediately he made the disciples get into the boat," <em>ēnagkasen tous mathētas embēnai eis to ploion</em>) while he dismissed the crowd reflects John 6:15\xe2\x80\x99s account that the crowd intended to make him king by force. The dismissal of both disciples (who might have been swept into the crowd\xe2\x80\x99s enthusiasm) and crowd was politically necessary to prevent a Messianic acclamation movement that would trigger Herodian or Roman response. The crossing to the other side separated both groups from each other and from the immediate political danger.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"After dismissing the crowds, he went up on the mountain by himself to pray" — solitary mountain prayer is a recurring practice in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s portrayal of Jesus (4:1; 14:23; 26:36-46). In the Jewish tradition, mountains were places of divine encounter (Sinai, Horeb, Carmel); the prophets and Moses had their defining encounters with God on mountains. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 prayer following the feeding miracle and the crowd\xe2\x80\x99s royal-acclamation impulse reflects the consistent Johannine-Synoptic pattern: Jesus received divine authority but consistently refused its political application.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The boat "beaten by the waves, for the wind was against them" (<em>basanizomenon hypo tōn kymatōn, ēn gar enantios ho anemos</em>) describes the katabatic winds (cold air descending from the Golan Heights into the Sea of Galilee basin) that could produce sudden squalls on the lake. The Sea of Galilee (208 meters below sea level) is surrounded by hills that channel strong winds down into the basin; fishermen on the lake knew these conditions well. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 experience of a storm while crossing the lake was not unusual — their terror was at what they saw on the water.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The fourth watch of the night (<em>tetartē̄ de phylakē̄ tēs nyktos</em>) corresponds to 3-6 AM in the Roman four-watch night division (6 PM-9 PM; 9 PM-midnight; midnight-3 AM; 3-6 AM). The fourth watch is the darkest and most exhausted period of the night, long after any natural expectation of rescue. The timing underscores both the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 prolonged distress and Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 knowledge of their situation despite his absence on the mountain.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"When the disciples saw him walking on the sea, they were terrified, saying \'It is a ghost!\'" — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 immediate interpretation of a figure walking on water was a <em>phantasma</em> (apparition, ghost). In Greco-Roman and Jewish belief systems, the sea was associated with the dead (the spirits of the drowned wandered near the sea in popular belief); a figure moving on the water at night was the most natural candidate for a ghost. Their cry of fear reflects a genuine terror produced by the combination of the storm and the inexplicable apparition.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"Take heart; it is I. Do not be afraid" — the self-identification "it is I" (<em>egō eimi</em>) employs the divine name formula from the OT theophany tradition (Exod 3:14; Isa 41:4; 43:10; 48:12). In the storm-sea context, the command "do not be afraid" parallels the OT theophany commands given to those who encountered divine presence (Gen 15:1; 26:24; Dan 10:12). The "I AM" formula on the water constitutes a claim to identity with the God who controls the waters (Job 9:8: "who alone stretched out the heavens and trampled the waves of the sea").</p>',
    "28": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s request — "Lord, if it is you, command me to come to you on the water" — is characteristic of Peter\xe2\x80\x99s impulsive testing of claims (cf. 16:22\xe2\x80\x99s rebuking Jesus; 26:33\xe2\x80\x99s boast about faithfulness). The condition "if it is you" (<em>ei sy ei</em>) is a test of identity, not a lack of faith. The request to come on the water is audaciously faith-filled; the subsequent sinking demonstrates the instability of faith not rooted in continuous attention to Jesus.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s walking on the water in response to Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 command "come" (<em>elthe</em>) is unique to Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s account (absent from Mark and John\xe2\x80\x99s versions of the walking-on-water). The detail serves both to honor Peter as the community\xe2\x80\x99s leader (his faith enabled remarkable action) and to illustrate the lesson about sustained vs. momentary faith. Peter actually walks on the water, demonstrating that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 word gives capability beyond natural human limits.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"But when he saw the wind, he was afraid, and beginning to sink he cried out, \'Lord, save me!\'" — the shift from walking to sinking follows the shift of attention from Jesus to the wind. The <em>blepōn de ton anemon</em> (seeing the wind) is paradoxical — wind is invisible; what he saw were the effects of the wind (the waves, the spray). His fear at the natural conditions overwhelmed his trust in the supernatural word that had enabled his walking. The immediate cry "Lord, save me!" (<em>Kyrie, sōson me</em>) is the shortest possible prayer — raw need addressed to the only available source of help.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Jesus immediately reached out his hand and took hold of him" — the immediate rescue responds to the immediate prayer, contrasting with the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 prolonged storm ordeal. The rebuke — "O you of little faith, why did you doubt?" (<em>oligopiste, eis ti edistasas</em>) — uses Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s characteristic term <em>oligopistia</em> (little faith), applied in Matthew to the disciples at several points of crisis (6:30; 8:26; 16:8; 17:20). Little faith is not absent faith — Peter got out of the boat — but faith that could not sustain itself under pressure.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The wind ceasing when Jesus and Peter entered the boat repeats the pattern of 8:26 (Jesus rebuked the wind and the sea, and there was a great calm). The second storm-stilling in Matthew reinforces the identity claim: Jewish tradition consistently associated control of the sea and storms with YHWH (Ps 65:7; 89:9; 107:23-30; Isa 51:15). The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 response — "Truly you are the Son of God" — is the appropriate theological conclusion drawn from the theophanic evidence.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Those in the boat worshiped him, saying, \'Truly you are the Son of God\'" — this is the first explicit worship of Jesus by the Twelve in Matthew (the magi worshiped in 2:11; a leper in 8:2; a ruler in 9:18). The title "Son of God" in Matthew carries a range of meaning from the Davidic messianic title (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 2:7) to the divine-identity claim implied by the sea-walking theophany. This moment of corporate confession anticipates Peter\xe2\x80\x99s Caesarea Philippi confession (16:16) and the Centurion\xe2\x80\x99s confession at the cross (27:54).</p>',
    "34": '<p>The landing at Gennesaret (<em>Gennēsaret</em>) places the boat on the northwestern shore of the Sea of Galilee, south of Capernaum. Gennesaret was a fertile plain about 5 km long and 2 km wide, known in antiquity for its productive agriculture (Josephus, <em>War</em> 3.10.8 praises its soil and climate as producing an extraordinary variety of crops year-round). The landing here after the storm brings Jesus back to the central area of his Galilean ministry.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The men of Gennesaret recognizing Jesus and sending throughout the region (<em>apesteilan eis holēn tēn perichoron ekeinēn</em>) reflects the communication network of Galilean village culture: news of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 arrival traveled through the informal networks of family and trade relationships across the surrounding villages and countryside. People who sought healing brought their sick on mats (<em>klinais</em>) — the same word used for the paralytic\xe2\x80\x99s mat in 9:2, connecting the two healing periods.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"They begged him that they might only touch the fringe of his garment" (<em>hapsōntai tou kraspedou tou himatiou autou</em>) echoes the hemorrhaging woman\xe2\x80\x99s healing in 9:20 (who touched the fringe/tassel). The news of that healing had evidently spread throughout the Galilee region; people were now deliberately replicating her approach. The fringe (<em>kraspedon</em>, the tzitzit/tassel required by Num 15:38-40) was the garment\xe2\x80\x99s ritually significant element; the connection to Mal 4:2\xe2\x80\x99s "healing in his wings/fringes" may underlie the practice. All who touched it were made well (<em>diesōthēsan</em>).</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew', existing)
    print('Matthew 13-14 mkt-context written.')
    for ch in ['13', '14']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
